This is a known breaking change. Android deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` (API 30+), and .NET MAUI 10 no longer supports `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize`. The modern fix is to listen to **IME (keyboard) insets** via `AndroidX.Core` and adjust your layout's bottom padding.

### 1. Set your activity to `AdjustNothing` (AndroidManifest.xml or startup)

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;

[Activity(/* existing attributes */,
          WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustNothing)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

### 2. Listen to keyboard insets and adjust padding

Create a helper you call from your chat page:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/KeyboardInsetHelper.cs
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;

namespace YourApp.Platforms.Android;

public static class KeyboardInsetHelper
{
    public static void Attach(IView mauiView)
    {
        var handler = mauiView.Handler;
        if (handler?.PlatformView is not global::Android.Views.View nativeView)
            return;

        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(nativeView, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
    }

    private class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(
            global::Android.Views.View view, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Use the larger of keyboard or nav-bar bottom inset
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);

            view.SetPadding(
                view.PaddingLeft, view.PaddingTop, view.PaddingRight, bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

### 3. Wire it up in your chat page

```xml
<!-- ChatPage.xaml -->
<Grid x:Name="RootGrid" RowDefinitions="*,Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" ... />
    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" Command="{Binding SendCommand}" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

```csharp
// ChatPage.xaml.cs
protected override void OnHandlerChanged()
{
    base.OnHandlerChanged();
#if ANDROID
    Platforms.Android.KeyboardInsetHelper.Attach(RootGrid);
#endif
}
```

### How it works

| Old (.NET 9) | New (.NET 10) |
|---|---|
| `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` told Android to shrink the window | `AdjustNothing` + IME insets — you read the keyboard height from `WindowInsetsCompat` and add matching bottom padding yourself |

The `WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime()` inset reports the keyboard's exact pixel height (0 when closed), so your input bar slides up precisely above it. This is the same mechanism first-party Android apps use post-API 30.

**iOS** doesn't need this — MAUI's `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` handles it. If you want to scope the Android code cleanly, the `#if ANDROID` guard keeps it platform-specific.
